  "title": "Public Health and Epidemiology",
  "abstract": "The management of harmful algal blooms (HAB) is a challenging task in a changing, and often unpredictable, coastal marine or freshwater environment. This chapter provides some guidance for HAB managers to facilitate the management process from a public health perspective. It explores the engagement between HAB managers, public health professionals, and coastal communities responding to HAB problems. The chapter presents a review of the exposure risks, symptoms, and general clinical management of the known HAB-related human health syndromes such as paralytic shellfish poisoning (PSP), amnesic shellfish poisoning (ASP), neurotoxic shellfish poisoning (NSP), brevetoxin inhalation syndrome (BIS), diarrhetic shellfish poisoning (DSP), ciguatera fish poisoning (CFP), azaspiracid shellfish poisoning(AZP) and toxic cyanobacteria. Illness prevention represents a critical component of HAB-manager activity. The chapter provides more general guidance for the role of the HAB manager. Coastal communities and their residents are vulnerable to a wide range of distress as a result of HAB events.",
